      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Now I have a very comprehensive picture. Let me summarize everything:\n\n## Complete Audio Diagnosis\n\n### FxSound Audio Enhancer (PRIMARY SUSPECT)\n- **Version**: 1.1.15.0 (from March 2022 - 4+ years old!)\n- **Kernel driver**: fxvad.sys dated March 2021 (5+ years old!)\n- **CPU**: 100% usage (!!!) - this is extremely abnormal\n- **Memory**: 18.3 MB working set\n- **Handles**: 328\n- **Threads**: 3\n- **Running since**: June 23, 2026 07:17:19 (2+ days continuously)\n- **Setting**: \"Voice\" preset with power=1 (enhancement ON)\n- **Output device**: Speaker/Headphone (Realtek High Definition Audio)\n- **Log**: Only records startup timestamps, no actual error logging\n\n### The Problem Chain\n\n1. **FxSound Audio Enhancer** sits between all audio output and your Realtek speakers\n2. It uses a **kernel-mode virtual audio driver** (fxvad.sys) from 2021\n3. It's consuming **100% CPU** continuously\n4. This causes **audio buffer underruns** (the audio data isn't processed fast enough)\n5. Buffer underruns = **crackling/popping noises**\n\n### Contributing Factors\n\n1. **Realtek HD Audio driver** is from May 2019 (7+ years old) - RTKVHD64.sys 6.0.8703.1\n2. **FxSound kernel driver** is from March 2021 (5+ years old)\n3. **3 unexpected shutdowns** in recent history (June 17, 20 June twice) - system instability\n4. **FxSound has been running for 2+ days straight** without restart\n5. **Multiple audio devices** active: Realtek, Intel HDMI, NVIDIA Virtual, FxSound - potential conflicts\n6. **Andrea USB headset** is phantom/disconnected - could cause routing issues\n\n### Why FxSound at 100% CPU?\n\nThe FxSound log shows only startup timestamps - no actual diagnostic info. But at 100% CPU with only 3 threads, it's likely:\n- Stuck in an infinite processing loop\n- The \"Voice\" preset with power=1 enhancement is overprocessing\n- The old kernel driver (2021) may be incompatible with current Windows updates\n- Memory leak or handle leak (328 handles for a simple audio enhancer is high)\n\n### Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe crackling is almost certainly caused by **FxSound intercepting and overprocessing all audio output** through its aging kernel driver, consuming 100% CPU, causing buffer underruns in the audio pipeline.\n\n### Recommended Fix Plan\n\n1. **Kill FxSound process** immediately to test if crackling stops\n2. **Disable FxSound from startup** \n3. **Uninstall FxSound** completely\n4. **Update Realtek audio drivers** (from 2019 to current)\n5. **Clean up phantom audio devices**\n6. **Test audio without FxSound** - if crackling is gone, FxSound was the cause\n7. If user wants audio enhancement, install a modern alternative or use Windows built-in audio enhancements\n\nI should present this plan to the user and ask if they want me to proceed.",
      "timestamp": 1782381700601
    },
